pr_review_comment_body:
I propose adding

```
    /// Custom metaclass (optional)
    handle metaclass;
```

below the ``doc`` member

> 1. I can't map on a generic "PathStat" without giving PathStat a weird and specific drop_leading_component method

Hm, yea... probably not worth it unless we do it in more than one place.

> 2. components().skip() returns a Skip<Component>, and it's non-obvious how to collect that into a Path...

Yep: that's annoying. But it looks like the following does work (from the examples in the PathBuf docs):
```
fs::PathStat::File {
  path: path.iter().skip(1).collect(),
  stat: stat,
}
```

----

So, code-golfed down (less than you were hoping for), this becomes:
```
paths
  .into_iter()
  .filter(|s| s.path().components().count() == 1)
  .map(|s| match s {
    fs::PathStat::File { path, stat } => {
      fs::PathStat::File {
        path: path.iter().skip(1).collect(),
        stat: stat,
      }
    }
    fs::PathStat::Dir { path, stat } => {
      fs::PathStat::Dir {
        path: path.iter().skip(1).collect(),
        stat: stat,
      }
    }
  })
  .collect()
```

I would prefer:

```python
try:
    date = datetime.datetime.strptime(value, '%Y')
except ValueError:
    try:
        date = datetime.datetime.strptime(value, '%Y-%m')
    except ValueError:
        return None
    else:
        return Period((MONTH, Instant((date.year, date.month, 1)), 1))
else:
    return Period((YEAR, Instant((date.year, date.month, 1)), 1))
```

It's less readable, but it wraps only the `strptime` calls in a `try/except`

The catch-all is very sneaky, could catch any error you don't want to catch, and I would always insist to avoid it!

> Each line can fail, and respectively raise a ValueError, AttributeError, ImportError or TypeError.

```python
invalid_error_message = u'ERROR: ...'.format(...)

tax_benefit_system = None

try:
    [reform_package, reform_name] = reform_path.rsplit('.', 1)
except ValueError:
    log.exception(invalid_reform_message)
else:
    try:
        reform_module = importlib.import_module(reform_package)
    except ImportError:
        log.exception(invalid_reform_message)
    else:
        reform = getattr(reform_module, reform_name, None)
        if reform is not None:
            try:
                tax_benefit_system = reform(tax_benefit_system)
            except Exception:
                log.exception(invalid_reform_message)

return tax_benefit_system
```

This is absolutely not tested and I agree it's longer, but more secure, and can be perhaps simplified.

