@pratyakshs One another way to computes samples would be by looping over the variables rather than looping over the number of samples we want. Taking the example in the doctest and let's say we want 1000 samples, we will start with 'diff' and compute all the 1000 samples for it by a single `sample_discrete` call, then can compute all the 1000 samples for 'intel` and since now we have the states of all the 1000 samples of `intel` and `diff` we can compute the values for `grade`. 
This method should be much faster and will also give us some space to vectorize computations. For starters for a call on 5 vars for 10000 samples we will need to call `sample_discrete` only 5 times instead of 50000 times.
Also, this method will give us space for memoization reduce calls.

This is equivalent:
```js
    methods: {
      url: (urlName, ...args) => { kolibriGlobal.urls[urlName](...args); },
    },
```
